e places called Reville, in Manche, Meuse, and Loiret."]},{"name":"Revel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gaston, Henri, Pascal.","French: habitational name from any of the places so named, for example in Isère and Haute-Garonne.","French: nickname from Old French, Occitan <i>reveau</i> ‘rebel’."]},{"name":"Revels","meanings":["English (Cumberland and Yorkshire): variant of   Revell  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Scottish: habitational name from Raffles in Mouswald (Dumfriesshire), comprising Old Norse <i>ref-hol</i> ‘fox-hole’ in a Scots plural form."]},{"name":"Reveal","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Revell  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Revell was born about 1265. She married Sir Mauger le Vavasour about 1286, in Denton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"about 1265–":"umbes 1265–Surnud","1265–1330":"1265–1330","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1305–1346":"1305–1346","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","1305":"1305","1346":"1346","abt 1305":"umbes 1305","1287":"1287","1265":"1265","1330":"1330","1295":"1295"